Set ARCOS R Package API Key

For this exercise, we will be working with subsets of the DEAs ARCOS database, which documented shipments of 76 billion opioid pills between 2006 and 2012, during the peak of the opioid epidemic.

The data was obtained after a lengthy legal battle by the Washington Post and the Charleston Gazette-Mail, and released by the Washington Post in raw and aggregated form. Washington Post Digging into the DEAs pain pill database page.

A data dictionary is available here: ARCOS Registrant Handbook.

Were going to load opioid data exclusively from the arcos R package API ARCOS API produced by the Washington Post, instead of uploading csvs and tsvs.

Remember, we need to store a password of sorts called an API key that will give us permission to access their data. Heres a list of API keys that will work.

Store the key first.

# store one of our API keys as an object called key
key <- "uO4EK6I"

Load Data

Load the data youll need for this package and clean up the column names.

Build Exploratory Visualizations

Task: Build an exploratory visualization to show year-over-year pill totals in Logan County, West Virginia between 2006 and 2012. It should have the following attributes: * Chart Type: a bar chart, with one bar per year between 2006 and 2012. Make the bars forest green. * Axes: years on the x axis, pill totals on the y axis, with proper axis labels. The number for each year should be shown. Put commas in the pill totals on the y axis, so theyre readable.
* Text: put a descriptive title, subtitle and source line. The title should describe the main takeaway.

You should also write up a few sentences explaining the trend in a bit more detail.

logan_county_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV", buyer_county == "LOGAN") %>%
  select(year, dosage_unit)

ggplot(logan_county_pills_per_year) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(year, dosage_unit), fill="forest green") +
  labs(x="Year", y="Total pills", title="Annual pill shipments to Logan County, WV remained high from 2006-2012", subtitle = "Total pills shipped to Logan County, WV by year", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma)

  # Also saves a web version
  ggsave("logan_pills.jpg", plot=last_plot())
  
#The amount of pills annually shipped to Logan County stayed stable over 6 million for the length of the ARCOS database, with slight peaks in 2008, 2009 and 2011.

Task: Build an exploratory visualization to show how year-over-year pill totals in Logan County, West Virginia between 2006 and 2012 compare to five other West Virginia counties with high levels of opioid shipments. It should have the following attributes: * Chart Type: six small multiple bar charts, arranged in a 3 x 2 grid. There should be one bar chart per county. * Counties: one chart per county for the following counties: Kanawha, Cabell, Mingo, Raleigh, Logan and Wood. * Axes: years on the x axis, pill totals on the y axis, with proper axis labels. The number for each year should be shown. Put commas in the pill totals on the y axis, so theyre readable. Rotate the year labels so theyre readable.
* Text: put a descriptive title, subtitle and source line. The title should describe the main takeaway.

You should also write up a few sentences explaining the trends in a bit more detail.

view(wv_pills_per_year)

wv_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV", (buyer_county %in% c("KANAWHA", "CABELL", "MINGO", "RALEIGH","LOGAN", "WOOD"))) %>%
  select(buyer_county, year, dosage_unit)

 ggplot(wv_pills_per_year) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(year, dosage_unit, fill=buyer_county)) +
  labs(x="Year", y="Total pills", title="Steady rise in opioids in six large West Virginia counties", subtitle = "Total pills per year shipped to Kanawha, Cabell, Mingo, Raleigh, Logan and Wood counties", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post", fill="County") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  facet_wrap(nrow=2, . ~ buyer_county) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  guides(fill="none")
